http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: This ontology module includes the necessary classes and properties to model energy assets.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/title.@value: Energy Asset: Energy Asset module for the FEDECOM Ontology

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A valve with three ports used to control the flow and mixing of fluids in heating or cooling circuits.
A device that conditions and circulates air as part of an HVAC system, typically including fans, filters, and heat exchangers.
The angular measurement in the horizontal plane between a reference direction (usually true north) and the direction of a solar panel.
A boiler that uses biomass (organic material) as fuel to produce heat or steam.
A burner designed to combust biomass fuel for heat generation.
A device that heats water or produces steam for heating or power generation.
A component that mixes fuel and air and initiates combustion to produce heat.
A damper that redirects airflow to maintain pressure or temperature balance in HVAC systems.
The coefficient of performance for cooling mode.
The coefficient of performance for heating mode.
The maximum amount of energy, power, or material that a system or component can store, produce, or handle under specified conditions.
A property or attribute that describes a specific feature or quality of an entity.
The rate at which energy or material is added to a storage system during charging.
A device that removes heat from a liquid via vapor-compression or absorption refrigeration.
A ratio that measures the efficiency of a heating or cooling system.
A tank used to store chilled water or other fluids for cooling applications.
A component that captures and transfers energy, typically solar thermal collectors for heat.
A system that simultaneously generates electricity and useful heat from a single energy source.
An individual part or element of a system that performs a specific function.
A high-efficiency gas boiler that recovers latent heat from exhaust gases by condensing water vapor.
A variable or setting used to regulate or adjust the behavior of a system or process.
A standard gas-fired boiler that heats water without condensing exhaust gases.
The efficiency with which a system converts one form of energy into another (e.g., chemical to electrical).
A device that regulates airflow in ducts or ventilation systems.
A physical or virtual entity designed to perform a specific function within a system, typically involving measurement, control, conversion, or communication of energy, signals, or materials.
The rate at which energy or material is removed from a storage system during discharging.
A centralized facility that produces heat and distributes it to multiple buildings through a network.
A device that supplies electric energy to recharge electric vehicle batteries.
A physical location equipped with an EV charger for vehicle charging.
The ratio of useful output (energy, power, or work) to the total input.
A boiler that uses electrical energy to heat water or produce steam.
The efficiency of converting electrical energy into useful work or another energy form.
A device that converts electrical energy into heat.
A meter that measures electrical energy consumption
A device that uses electricity to split water into hydrogen and oxygen through electrolysis.
The amount of energy transferred per unit of time through a system or component.
A fan or device that removes air, fumes, or gases from a space.
A unit consisting of a fan and a heat exchanger coil used for heating or cooling air.
The volume or mass of a substance (e.g., fluid, gas) passing through a point or system per unit of time.
A device that converts chemical energy from hydrogen or other fuels into electricity through electrochemical reactions.
A heat recovery device that captures heat from exhaust fumes for reuse.
A meter that measures energy exchanged between a building and the electrical grid.
A tank specifically designed to store hydrogen safely under controlled conditions.
Heating, Ventilation, and Air Conditioning equipment that regulate indoor climate.
A meter that measures thermal energy consumption.
A tank that stores thermal energy, typically in the form of hot water or other heat-retaining materials.
A device that converts energy (typically electrical, thermal, or chemical) into heat for the purpose of warming air, water, or other substances within a system or space.
A heating circuit designed to operate at high temperatures, typically for industrial or specialized applications.
A sensor that measures both humidity and temperature in an environment.
A device that measures and records the consumption or flow of energy or resources.
The predefined boundaries or thresholds within which a system or component can operate safely and effectively.
A photovoltaic system that converts solar energy into electrical energy using solar panels and associated components.
The rate at which energy is transferred, converted, or consumed by a system or component.
The rate at which power is transmitted or distributed through a system.
The maximum continuous power that a device or system can deliver or handle under specified conditions.
A measure of the opposition to the flow of electric current.
A device that detects and measures physical properties (e.g., temperature, pressure, light) and converts them into signals for monitoring or control.
An advanced meter that records consumption and communicates data digitally for monitoring and control.
A container designed to store liquids or gases for later use.
The total internal volume of a tank designed to store fluids or gases.
A meter installed downstream of a main meter to measure consumption for a specific area or device.
The efficiency of converting thermal energy into useful work or another energy form.
A tank that stores thermal energy for heating or cooling purposes, often using phase-change materials or water.
The angle between a surface (e.g., solar panel) and the horizontal plane.
An electrical device that changes the voltage level of alternating current (AC) in a power system.
The amount of three-dimensional space occupied by an object or substance.

Specifies the type of connection configuration for an asset.
Allowed values:

parallel – Components are connected in parallel, sharing input and output points to maintain equal voltage.
series – Components are connected in sequence, so the same current flows through each component.
Indicates the azimuth angle associated with an asset, typically for orientation purposes.
Specifies the COP for heating mode of an asset.
Specifies the COP for cooling mode of an asset.
Links an asset to its overall capacity (energy, power, or material).
Defines the range of capacity values for an asset (minimum and maximum).
Relates an asset to a specific characteristic or attribute that describes its properties.
Links an asset to the rate at which it charges energy or material
Links an asset to a charging point for electric vehicles or devices.
Associates an asset with its COP value, representing efficiency in heating or cooling.
Specifies the efficiency of an asset in converting one energy form to another.
Links an asset to the rate at which it discharges energy or material.
Relates an asset to its overall efficiency.
Specifies the electrical capacity of an asset, such as a battery or PV system.
Indicates the efficiency of electrical energy conversion for an asset.
Specifies the maximum power rating of an asset.
Associates an asset with its model identifier or specification.
Links an asset to its operational boundaries or thresholds.
Associates an asset with its power value (rate of energy transfer).
Specifies the maximum power rating of an asset.
Links an asset to its electrical resistance value.
Indicates the target value or setpoint for controlling an asset (e.g., temperature, pressure).
Represents the current operational state of an asset.
Associates an asset with its ability to store energy or material.
Links an asset to the volume of its storage tank.
Relates an asset with the space it works for.
Relates an asset to its thermal capacity, indicating heat storage or transfer capability.
Indicates the efficiency of thermal energy conversion for an asset.
Indicates the tilt angle of an asset (e.g., solar panel).
Associates an asset with its physical volume.
Boolean property indicating whether an asset functions as generation equipment.
Defines a hierarchical relationship where a sub-meter asset belongs to a main meter asset.
Specifies the number of panels associated with a PV system.
